Title - Presidents of the 19th Century

Subtitle 1 - Thomas Jefferson
Paragraph - Thomas Jefferson (April 13, 1743 – July 4, 1826) - Served as the third
President of the United States from 1801 to 1809. During the American Revolution,
Jefferson was one of the primary authors of The Declaration of Independence,
He also served as the second Governor of Virginia. After the war, Jefferson
served as the first U.S. Secretary of State, and eventually founded the
Jeffersonian Republican Party.

Subtitle 2 - Abraham Lincoln
Paragraph - Abraham Lincoln (February 12, 1809 – April 15, 1865) - Served as the
16th President of the United States from 1861 until his assassination in 1865.
Lincoln led the U.S. during one of its' greatest trials and tribulations, the American
Civil War. Under his leadership, Great Britain was kept out of the war, the slaves
were freed, and the Confederacy was defeated. Due to his skill as a statesman,
Lincoln is consistently regarded as the greatest U.S. President.

Subtitle 3 - Ulysses S. Grant
Paragraph - Ulysses S. Grant (April 27, 1822 – July 23, 1885) - Served as the 18th
President of the United States from 1869 to 1877. Grant led the Union Army to victory
in the Civl War and served as U.S. Secretary of War. As a member of the Radical
Republicans, Grant was a staunch advocate for strict Reconstruction, and fought for
civil rights for freedmen. During his Presidency, Grant appointed many African-Americans
and Jewish-Americans to positions of government, prosecuted the Ku Klux Klan, and
supported the ratification of the 15th Amendment
